                    <div class="popup__column">
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/brexit" title="The trade unions are very concerned about the UK&amp;rsquo;s departure from the European Union and its impact on workers both in Britain and the Member States. The ETUC&amp;rsquo;s position is found in a statement agreed by the Executive Committee in March 2017. 

The ETUC is working closely with its TUC affiliate in the UK. The TUC opposed Brexit, and since the referendum has been active in defending workers&amp;rsquo; rights, calling on the British government to consult trade unions throughout the negotiations. The ETUC has demanded a similar guarantee from EU leaders.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/390">Brexit</a>
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item main-menu-item--has-child has-dropdown" data-a11y-toggle="collective-bargaining-wage-policy--pay-rise-campaign">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/collective-bargaining-wage-policy-pay-rise-campaign" title="The ETUC wants stronger collective bargaining systems and binding agreements at national level covering workers in both public and private sectors, including workers in SMEs, to promote quality employment, equality, decent wages, pay increases and social progress. We demand respect for all agreements concluded in the framework of social dialogue at all levels.

Workers across Europe need a pay rise. Negotiations between social partners at the relevant level are the best tool to secure good wages and working conditions. Wage-setting should remain a national matter and take place in line with national practices and industrial relations systems. In 2017-2018 the ETUC coordinated&amp;nbsp;a successful&amp;nbsp;Europe-wide campaign for a pay rise for all working people, but especially for lower-paid workers such as women, young people, and those living in less prosperous EU Member States (upward wage convergence). It is currently working to influence the European Commission&#039;s proposals on fair minimum wages.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/44">Collective bargaining, wage policy &amp; pay rise campaign</a>
                                  
  
                    
              <div class="popup__item-nested">
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/issue/transnational-company-agreements-tca" title="Progressing toward a European&amp;nbsp;optional legal framework for Transnational Company Agreements:

In line with the 2015 Paris Congress and Executive Committee decisions, the ETUC has&amp;nbsp;put forward a concept example for a European Optional Legal Framework (OLF) for Transnational Company Agreements (TCAs). This would help clarify the leading role of the European Trade Union Federations (ETUFs) in negotiations as well as the interaction between different levels of collective bargaining and the effectiveness of such agreements. The ETUC proposal is based on the following documents – the so-called ‘OLF package’ – which has&amp;nbsp;been developed over recent years:


	ETUC report Towards a Legal Framework for Transnational Company Agreements;
	ETUC report Building an enabling environment for voluntary and autonomous negotiations at transnational level between trade unions and multinational companies;
	ETUC concept example of a possible&amp;nbsp;OLF for TCAs;
	European Parliament Resolution on Cross-border collective bargaining and transnational social dialogue - Rapporteur Thomas Händel MEP, adopted on 12 September 2013.

" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/383">Transnational Company Agreements (TCA)</a>
                      </div>
                </div>
            
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/digitalisation-and-platform-economy-atypical-work" title="The growth of digital platforms has created new forms of work organisation and labour outsourcing. The status of platform workers is often unclear, leaving them without access to social security, training, health and safety protection, or workers’ rights including the right to organise and bargain collectively through a trade union. The COVID-19 crisis has placed this insecurity in sharp focus. The ETUC insists that platforms should recognise their responsibility towards their workers, ensuring fair wages, security and social protection including sick pay and insurance. Dependent self-employed and freelancers should also benefit from social and trade union rights.

The ETUC is not opposed to digitalisation, but it should always improve working conditions and be developed in cooperation with workers and trade unions. The gender perspective must be at the core of all digital initiatives, increasing women’s participation in STEM sectors: (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) and avoiding gender bias in algorithms.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/308">Digitalisation and platform economy / Atypical Work</a>
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/economic-and-social-cohesion" title="The principles of cohesion and solidarity – economic, social and territorial – are enshrined in the EU Treaty and are vital for EU integration. The Treaty of Lisbon stresses that “the Union shall aim at reducing disparities between the levels of development of the various regions and the backwardness of the least favoured regions”.

Economic, social and territorial cohesion must continue to be at the core of the Europe 2020 strategy. Major differences between EU regions and within Member States still exist, hence the importance of the European Regional Development Funds (ERDF) and the Cohesion Fund (CF).&amp;nbsp;EU cohesion policy needs to support regional development, sustainable growth and quality employment. The General Regulation for the European Structural and Investment Funds for 2014-2020 strengthens these priorities, including (notably the European Social Fund) employment, fair mobility, the fight against poverty, social inclusion, education and training.

The European Code of Conduct concerning Partnership, issued by the European Commission in line with the partnership principle, set out in Article 5 of the new Structural Fund Regulation, must be actively implemented.

&amp;nbsp;
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/23">Economic  and Social Cohesion</a>
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item main-menu-item--has-child has-dropdown" data-a11y-toggle="economic-governance---european-semester">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/economic-governance-european-semester" title="The ETUC demands a complete reform of the existing EU economic governance system, to end austerity, encourage investment, and stop putting pressure on wages and collective bargaining. Deeper European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) must be matched by a strong social dimension, with social and environmental indicators as an integral feature.&amp;nbsp; Trade unions at national level should be closely involved in formulating and implementing national reform plans and country specific recommendations.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/181">Economic Governance / European Semester</a>
                                  
  
                    
              <div class="popup__item-nested">
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/issue/economic-and-social-crisis" title="The 2008 economic crisis, caused largely by unregulated and often unlawful banking and financial gambling and speculation, left an ongoing legacy of depression, unemployment, hardship, poverty and social upheaval. It led to cuts in wages, job losses, and the destruction of well-established systems of social dialogue between governments, employers and trade unions. Secure jobs have turned into precarious contracts, public services and social protection have been slashed, and the backlash has unfairly targeted migrants and other vulnerable groups in society. 

Structural reforms alone will not remedy the problems. The ETUC has called for a New Path for Europe, with investment of 2% of GDP over 10 years, to bring new jobs and secure growth. 
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/35">Economic and Social crisis</a>
                      </div>
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/issue/european-semester" title="European Countries are economically interdependent and the European semester cycle coordinates their fiscal, economic and social policies. This is based on an intergovernmental approach creating a worrying democratic deficit. A unified and coordinated trade union response is necessary to make workers&amp;rsquo; voices heard at both European and national level. The ETUC and its affiliates are stepping up their joint efforts to strengthen their involvement in this policy-making process so as to promote workers&amp;rsquo; interests. Used in the past to impose failed austerity measures, the Semester should now boost economic recovery and relaunch the European social model. The European Semester needs to become a driver for fairer economic and social governance of the EMU. For this to happen, trade unions should be closely involved in formulating and implementing national reform plans and country specific recommendations.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/278">European Semester</a>
                      </div>
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/issue/monetary-and-fiscal-policies" title="Higher taxes on the highest incomes are needed to redistribute wealth and tackle soaring inequality, and increase public revenues and spending. The ETUC supports the introduction of an EU-wide Financial Transactions Tax (FTT) and a common corporate tax of at least 25%. 

In recent years, shocking levels of tax evasion and fraud, tax avoidance, and tax competition through preferential tax rates for international companies have been uncovered across Europe. They lead to a loss of public funds and general disillusionment with unfair policies that penalise the poor while offering massive benefits to the very rich. These practices must end, and the criminal perpetrators punished.&amp;nbsp;
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/36">Monetary and fiscal policies</a>
                      </div>
                </div>
            
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/education-and-training" title="A well-educated workforce, together with a commitment to research and innovation, is a prerequisite for sustainable growth and social cohesion. The ETUC pursues quality education for all, together with vocational training and lifelong learning, regardless of age or gender.

Learning paths must not only supply the labour market and help generate quality jobs, they should also support personal development and welfare. More public investment is needed, but private companies should also provide ongoing training to equip workers with the skills they need, taking account of digitalisation and new technologies.&amp;nbsp;
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/45">Education and Training</a>
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item main-menu-item--has-child has-dropdown" data-a11y-toggle="employment---labour-market-policy">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/employment-labour-market-policy" title="The ETUC&amp;rsquo;s objective is full employment in Europe and quality jobs for all. We oppose precarious contracts and undeclared work, bogus self-employment and abusive employment practices. Instead, we fight and negotiate for secure employment contracts, good working conditions and respect for workers&amp;rsquo; rights, in both private and public sectors. Decent pay &amp;ndash; best achieved through collective bargaining by strong trade unions &amp;ndash; remains the best route to ending in-work poverty. The ETUC is particularly active in demanding equal pay for women, and an end to unpaid internships and poverty wages for young people.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/133">Employment / Labour Market Policy</a>
                                  
  
                    
              <div class="popup__item-nested">
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/issue/labour-market-policy" title="The ETUC demands coordinated labour market policies across the EU to improve labour standards for everyone. In many Member States, workers have had to pay the price for the short-sighted and self-defeating measure of cutting funding to active labour market policies.&amp;nbsp; The European Employment Strategy (EES) must aim to create good quality, sustainable jobs in all Member States. The ETUC opposes structural reforms that undermine employment protection legislation and collective bargaining.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/84">Labour market policy</a>
                      </div>
                </div>
            
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/energy-policy" title="Europe needs an energy transition towards a low-carbon economy based mainly on renewable energies and greater energy efficiency. This would create new jobs while at the same time reducing dependency on energy imports and releasing financial resources to be invested in new technologies and innovation. It would also improve air quality and reduce the number of related diseases.

The ETUC calls for an EU just transition strategy based on a just transition fund, as well as a governance framework that involves trade unions and encourages Member States to anticipate changes facing the workforce due to decarbonisation.

The ETUC supports the objectives of the Energy Union and an EU energy policy based on solidarity, sustainability, security of supply and affordability, and monitors its implementation carefully.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/14">Energy Policy</a>
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item main-menu-item--has-child has-dropdown" data-a11y-toggle="equality-and-non-discrimination">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/equality-and-non-discrimination" title="The ETUC is a leader in the fight for human rights and equality, and committed to solidarity, equal respect and dignity for all. We work closely with NGOs active at European level in opposing unfair treatment, including discrimination against refugees, asylum-seekers, undeclared and cross-border workers. The ETUC has lobbied in favour of the horizontal equality directive currently blocked by the Council.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/77">Equality and non-discrimination</a>
                                  
  
                    
              <div class="popup__item-nested">
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/issue/disability" title="Disabled people of working age still face massive discrimination in the workplace. As Europe&amp;rsquo;s population ages, older people also face obstacles that prevent them living in dignity and participating in society. The ETUC works with the European Disability Forum and other NGOs to promote equality and maintain vital public services.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/34">Disability</a>
                      </div>
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/issue/lesbian-gay-bisexual-and-transgender-rights" title="The ETUC is committed to equal treatment and respect for lesbians, gay men, bisexuals and transgender workers (LGBTQI).

The EU has a legal framework to protect workers against discrimination on grounds of sexual orientation or gender identity. One Directive is already binding in all Member States.

But research has shown that there is a lack of awareness throughout Europe &amp;ndash; including in trade unions &amp;ndash; that the EU prohibits discrimination on grounds of sexual orientation.&amp;nbsp; The ETUC has published a leaflet, available in 22 languages, to help members promote LGBTQI workers&amp;rsquo; rights.

Following the adoption of ETUC recommendations on actions and activities promoting equal rights, respect and dignity for workers regardless of their sexual orientation or gender identity, in December 2008, the ETUC lobbied the EU institutions for an EU Road Map on LGBTQI rights. It has also set up an LGBTQI rights trade union network to exchange information and develop joint actions among ETUC affiliates. LGBTQI rights are trade union rights.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/40">Lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender rights</a>
                      </div>
                </div>
            
                          </div>

          
                            
                    </div>
          <div class="popup__column">
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/european-pillar-social-rights" title="The European trade union movement supports the proposed European Pillar of Social Rights, but finds it falls well short of what workers and their families need, and should be strengthened.

Working people have been waiting since the crisis for concrete action to improve their standard of living, so trade unions will not let this opportunity slip away.

The ETUC


	Strongly supports better work-life balance, including paid paternity and carers’ leave;
	Wants a revised Written Statement Directive to cover all workers;
	Believes self-employed and ‘non-standard’ workers must have access to social protection.


A ‘European Day of Action’ will take place on 16 November 2017 - the day before the Gothenburg EU Social Summit is due to adopt the Pillar.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/301">European pillar of social rights</a>
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/european-social-dialogue" title="European social dialogue is at the heart of European Union governance. It enables the European social partners to help to define European social standards, and is a fundamental part of the European social model.

The ETUC is the only social partner representing workers at European level. The Treaty of Maastricht (1992) guarantees this formal status. Together with the EU-level employers, it is involved in consultation in areas such as employment, social affairs, macroeconomic dialogue, industrial and regional policies.

Dialogue between the European social partners takes place at both cross-sectoral and sectoral levels. The participants in the cross-sectoral dialogue, the ETUC, BusinessEurope (private sector employers), UEAPME (SMEs), and CEEP (public employers), concluded framework agreements on parental leave (1996) and revised in 2009, part-time work (1997) and fixed-term contracts (1999). They were ratified by the Council of Ministers and are now part of European legislation.

The social partners have also concluded autonomous agreements on telework (2002), work-related stress (2004), harassment and violence at work (2007), inclusive labour markets (2010) and on active ageing and an intergenerational approach (2017).

They have also adopted frameworks of action on lifelong development of competencies and qualifications (2002), gender equality (2005) and youth employment (2013).

In July 2015, the EU Social Partners adopted their fifth multiannual work programme (2015-2017). This covers active ageing; reconciliation of work, private and family life and gender equality; mobility and migration; investment and strengthening the industrial base; skills needs in digital economies; active labour market policies; apprenticeships and youth employment; capacity building and better implementation of European social dialogue outcomes.

The ETUC represents workers&amp;rsquo; interests in the Social Dialogue Committee, which meets three times a year.

Resource Centre Social Dialogue websites for workers and employers were set up in 2007 to enhance awareness and knowledge of EU social dialogue.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/43">European Social Dialogue</a>
                          </div>

          
                            
          
                        <div class="main-menu-item main-menu-item--has-child has-dropdown" data-a11y-toggle="external-relations">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/external-relations" title="In its international work, the ETUC cooperates with the International Trade Union Confederation (ITUC), its Pan-Regional Regional Council (PERC), ITUC regional and other organisations, to advance ETUC objectives worldwide, notably in promoting peace, development and social justice. It also works with the Council of Europe, EFTA and other European institutions which promote cooperation on matters affecting working people&amp;rsquo;s interests.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/89">External relations</a>
                                  
  
                    
              <div class="popup__item-nested">
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/issue/external-relations-geographical-area" title="The ETUC challenges the violation of trade union rights in countries outside the EU. It maintains relationships with trade unions in Eastern Europe through the Pan-European Regional Council (PERC), and in the Mediterranean region through the Euromed Trade Union Forum, which groups together trade union organisations that are members of the ETUC with those in partner countries of the Union for the Mediterranean (UfM).

The ETUC works with trade unions in the countries where the EU has free trade agreements, in particular through follow-up committees established by the EU institutions to monitor the agreements. This is the case in Colombia, Peru, Central American countries and South Korea. The ETUC maintains relations with regional trade union organisations such as the Trade Union Confederation of Americas (TUCA), within the framework of institutional cooperation between the EU and the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States (CELAC), and the Arab Trade Union Confederation.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/94">External Relations by geographical area</a>
                      </div>
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/theme/transatlantic-dialogue" title="The ETUC and the US trade union national centre, AFL-CIO, maintain a close relationship, further developed in the context of the TTIP (Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership) talks. The ETUC and the AFL-CIO issued a &amp;ldquo;Declaration of Joint Principles&amp;rdquo; in June 2014 and a joint statement in March 2016: TTIP negotiations &amp;#39;On the Wrong Course&amp;#39;. The ETUC takes part in the European Commission&amp;rsquo;s TTIP Advisory Group.

The ETUC also worked closely with the Canadian Labour Congress (CLC) in demanding changes to the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement with Canada (CETA).
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/98">Transatlantic dialogue</a>
