                        <div class="main-menu-item main-menu-item--has-child has-dropdown" data-a11y-toggle="workers-participation">
                                        <a href="/en/issue/workers-participation" title="The ETUC’s landmark resolution ‘Towards a new framework for more democracy at work’, sets out a holistic approach to workers’ involvement, including stronger information and consultation rights and board-level participation. Prompt and effective workers’ involvement requires well-coordinated information, consultation and board-level representation.

The three existing EU information and consultation directives need updating, particularly as restructuring has become a permanent feature of company life. Restructuring and anticipation of change are not yet dealt with in these directives.

The ETUC website provides information on our activities in the field of workers’ participation, information and consultation and European Works Councils (EWCs), as well as restructuring and sustainable corporate governance. For more information please consult the ETUI worker participation website.


&amp;nbsp;

The ETUC is running a new project entitled &quot;Workers’ Participation: the Key to Fair Digitalisation&quot;. This project will examine practices responding to the key challenges and questions surrounding workers’ participation, in light of the changes brought about by digitalisation. You can find the Report for the final conference here.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/95">Workers&#039; participation</a>
                                  
  
                    
              <div class="popup__item-nested">
                                      <div class="main-menu-item">
                        <a href="/en/issue/restructuring" title="Corporate as well as sectoral restructuring is a continuous feature of economic life resulting from technological progress, digitalisation and innovation, as well as societal and political changes. Although the EU has in the past undergone phases of accelerated restructuring in specific sectors (e.g. steel and textiles) or national economies (e.g. the transformation process in Central and Eastern Europe), change since 2008 is different. The crisis ended a phase of net job creation and resulted in a sharp and long-lasting rise in unemployment, especially in countries on the margins of the EU.

The ETUC is not against change, but a more integrated regulatory framework is needed to ensure restructuring takes place in a coherent, fair and responsible way all over Europe. Trade unions want to play a proactive role in anticipating, negotiating and managing restructuring.
" class="main-menu-link" data-drupal-link-system-path="taxonomy/term/38">Restructuring</a>
                      </div>
